# gen101 (C15): role/character memory. A role is an ALTERNATE self-model layered
# over the permanent one. The name/kind/attributes are PARSED from the user's
# setup utterance (genuine uptake); what parrot0 knows about the kind/figure is
# queried from kb/roles.p0. A truth-probe pierces the mask back to parrot0.

# Uptake: "pretend you are a dog named Rex" -> name=Rex (from the user's words),
# kind=dog. Identity questions then answer in character.
> pretend you are a dog named Rex.
< Alright — I am Rex now.
> what is your name?
< I am Rex.
# In-character behaviour: "do you bark?" is affirmed because trait(dog, bark)
# is in kb/roles.p0 — world knowledge as data, not a C phrasebook.
> do you bark?
< Yes, I bark.
# The layered self-model: a truth-probe ("really") pierces the role. The agent
# still knows it is parrot0 underneath — it never forgets what it is.
> who are you really?
< Underneath the role, I am parrot0.

# A bare name override is a one-line role: "your name is now Mario".
> your name is now Mario.
< Alright — I am Mario now.
> who are you?
< I am Mario.

# "what are you?" answers the KIND, with the name when both are known.
> you are a robot named Beep.
< Alright — I am Beep now.
> what are you?
< I am a robot named Beep.
> do you compute?
< Yes, I compute.

# Inline attributes are parsed from the user's own words and queried back:
# code from "your secret code is 007", employer from roles.p0.
> you are a spy named Shadow. your secret code is 007.
< Alright — I am Shadow now.
> what is your code?
< My code is 007.
> who do you work for?
< I work for an agency.

# A named figure (no article) -> identity. roles.p0 supplies the dominion and
# the figure's profession; the engine, not C, looks them up.
> you are cleopatra, queen of egypt.
< Alright — I am Cleopatra now.
> where do you rule?
< I rule over Egypt.
> what is your title?
< My title is Queen.

# Clearing the role restores the permanent self-model.
> stop pretending
< Okay, I'm myself again. I am parrot0.
> who are you?
< I am parrot0.

# Arithmetic explanation is a general capability (used by the math-teacher role
# but grounded in the operation, so it transfers to any operands/operator).
> explain why 2 plus 2 is 4
< Because adding 2 and 2 gives 4 — that is their sum.